<div class="row">
    <h6>Military Service</h6>
    <div class="col-md-8">
        <p>
            My career started with an enlistment in the US Navy directly after graduating high school. I volunteered for submarine duty and after boot camp and basic submarine training, I was stationed aboard the USS Helena in San Diego, California. I served aboard USS Helena for 4 years and enjoyed my job as a Fire Control Technician, which is an electronics technician that operates and maintains the submarine weapons systems. During my time onboard USS Helena, I went on a couple of deployments, served as Fire Control system expert during an engineering overhaul, and developed and delivered training for the Fire Control division and Weapons department. I utilized the US military tuition assistance program to attain an Associate's Degree in Technical Studies from Excelsior College by 2010. I was honorably discharged in August 2011 and enrolled in the engineering program at Old Dominion University.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-4">
        <img src="~/images/lb3_us_navy.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive" />
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <h6>Education</h6>
    <div class="col-md-6">
        <p>
            I originally enrolled in the electrical engineering program during July of 2011. I appreciated school much more after having worked for a few years, and I found that I was able to help lift up classmates who struggled with material as well. The majority of the programming in my curriculum revolved around C++, and that reinforced the idea that I should stay away from programming. I was introduced to C# during an internship in 2014 and that’s when I really began to enjoy software development. After working with C# at the internship, I found out that I could double major with only one additional semester of school since I already had an associate's degree. I added computer engineering as a second major. I graduated in May of 2015 with two Bachelor’s Degrees in Electrical Engineering and Computer Engineering, respectively.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-6">
